WEBVTT

1
00:02:07.751 --> 00:02:10.042
Where are you going?
- I'll be right back.

2
00:03:38.167 --> 00:03:42.126
You shouldn't have brought them.
- But dad is out there.

3
00:04:04.417 --> 00:04:11.167
Take cover. Port. get ready to fire.
- Get ready to fire.

4
00:04:11.292 --> 00:04:14.501
Hard to starboard.

5
00:04:32.251 --> 00:04:34.126
Admiral Tromp is trapped.

6
00:04:35.959 --> 00:04:38.084
Square away the yards.

7
00:04:38.209 --> 00:04:41.459
Michiel. this is madness.
- Luff up to port.

8
00:04:41.584 --> 00:04:44.834
Luff up to port.

9
00:04:47.417 --> 00:04:49.626
We can't leave Tromp to die.

10
00:05:01.751 --> 00:05:05.542
Chop it.
Chuck that mast overboard. Chop.

11
00:05:23.376 --> 00:05:26.917
We'll push those idiot English
back to their island.

12
00:05:27.042 --> 00:05:29.667
Until death. admiral.
- Go straight.

13
00:05:29.792 --> 00:05:32.126
Mainsail halyard.

14
00:05:36.959 --> 00:05:40.584
To port. - Get ready to tack.

15
00:05:44.626 --> 00:05:46.834
Get ready to fire.

16
00:06:37.167 --> 00:06:38.501
Michiel.

17
00:06:47.126 --> 00:06:48.751
Good work.

18
00:06:53.917 --> 00:06:55.834
The admiral...

19
00:07:02.834 --> 00:07:06.334
He's calling all captains.
Get a sloop ready.

20
00:07:06.459 --> 00:07:10.750
You want to row there?
- You. you and you jump in. come on.

21
00:07:37.209 --> 00:07:40.459
Michiel? You're just in time.

22
00:07:40.584 --> 00:07:44.292
You'll be all right.
- It's nothing.

23
00:07:45.792 --> 00:07:47.625
We'll get you to port.

24
00:07:47.750 --> 00:07:50.125
The wind is blowing the wrong way.

25
00:07:51.584 --> 00:07:56.334
Like politicians. very unpredictable.

26
00:07:56.459 --> 00:07:57.709
Don't talk.

27
00:07:57.834 --> 00:08:01.792
My men need someone like you.

28
00:08:03.250 --> 00:08:05.667
Someone who keeps his course.

29
00:08:06.709 --> 00:08:10.209
You can do it.

30
00:08:10.334 --> 00:08:11.834
Michiel.

31
00:08:31.000 --> 00:08:32.709
Go and help people.

32
00:08:43.542 --> 00:08:45.209
Are you all right? - Yes.

33
00:08:45.334 --> 00:08:47.792
This morning you also...
- I'm fine.

34
00:09:23.417 --> 00:09:28.959
The new prime minister
of Holland and West Friesland.

35
00:09:30.167 --> 00:09:35.667
The right honourable lord Johan de Witt.

36
00:09:37.667 --> 00:09:39.709
Thank you.

37
00:09:39.834 --> 00:09:42.167
As regent of the Prince of Orange...

38
00:09:42.292 --> 00:09:45.167
I think I speak on behalf
of all members...

39
00:09:45.292 --> 00:09:49.667
when I say we're glad with
our new chairman from mighty Holland.

40
00:09:52.875 --> 00:09:55.334
Some would say relieved.

41
00:09:56.375 --> 00:10:00.334
I. for one. will sleep better
now we have a man at the helm...

42
00:10:00.459 --> 00:10:03.834
who'll serve the interests
of all the provinces.

43
00:10:03.959 --> 00:10:07.084
And not just those
of his republican friends.

44
00:10:08.042 --> 00:10:13.625
I presume lord Kievit
can rise above the parties.

45
00:10:14.709 --> 00:10:17.334
I was thinking
of the Prince of Orange.

46
00:10:18.709 --> 00:10:23.084
How can the Prince
rise above the parties...

47
00:10:23.209 --> 00:10:25.750
when he doesn't even reach my belt?

48
00:10:29.459 --> 00:10:32.417
Order.

49
00:10:33.209 --> 00:10:36.584
We will hear the honourable De Witt.

50
00:10:38.667 --> 00:10:43.334
First. I'm very happy that lord Kievit
is sleeping well.

51
00:10:44.500 --> 00:10:50.917
To answer your question:
I understand your concerns. I do.

52
00:10:51.042 --> 00:10:55.750
There is no one in this country
who understands you more than I do.

53
00:10:59.834 --> 00:11:04.292
My father was imprisoned
for disagreeing with the Orangists.

54
00:11:05.292 --> 00:11:08.500
I found out what it means
to live in a country...

55
00:11:08.625 --> 00:11:11.500
where you cannot say
what you are thinking.

56
00:11:11.625 --> 00:11:15.209
Do you want to live in such a country?
I don't.

57
00:11:15.334 --> 00:11:17.375
I don't think you do. either.

58
00:11:18.834 --> 00:11:23.584
Let me pose you a question.
We're a nation of merchants.

59
00:11:23.709 --> 00:11:28.709
We sail the seas of the world
with 20.000 ships.

60
00:11:28.834 --> 00:11:30.959
In trade. we all work together.

61
00:11:31.084 --> 00:11:34.292
To get better prices
and to help each other.

62
00:11:35.542 --> 00:11:39.125
And what do you think?
Does this work or not?

63
00:11:39.750 --> 00:11:44.167
It does. Some members became so
successful they hardly fit in the benches.

64
00:11:47.334 --> 00:11:50.250
When you do business
in the East or the West...

65
00:11:50.375 --> 00:11:54.584
do you do so
as Orangists or as republicans?

66
00:11:54.709 --> 00:11:58.667
And why are the English trying
to block our shipping routes?

67
00:11:58.834 --> 00:12:03.667
To disrupt trade. Is that because
you're an Orangist or a republican?

68
00:12:03.834 --> 00:12:08.500
No. the English want to wage war
against us. because we're Dutch.

69
00:12:08.667 --> 00:12:10.084
Free Dutchmen.

70
00:12:15.042 --> 00:12:18.375
Large monarchies consider
our small nation too rich.

71
00:12:18.500 --> 00:12:23.792
Too successful and too free.
On top of that. we're a republic.

72
00:12:24.417 --> 00:12:28.334
In which all men are free
to live their own lives.

73
00:12:28.459 --> 00:12:30.875
We decide how we worship God.

74
00:12:31.000 --> 00:12:33.667
No leader is more important
than the country itself.

75
00:12:34.125 --> 00:12:38.917
The English begrudge us our freedom.
Our freedom frightens them.

76
00:12:39.042 --> 00:12:44.334
Because we're prepared
to die for our freedom.

77
00:12:44.459 --> 00:12:49.084
Because we paid for our freedom
with our own blood.

78
00:12:49.209 --> 00:12:51.000
And I'm asking you:

79
00:12:51.125 --> 00:12:55.625
Haven't you all lost a relative
to the Spanish or the English?

80
00:12:55.792 --> 00:12:59.959
And was that republican blood
or Orangist blood?

81
00:13:00.084 --> 00:13:01.084
No.

82
00:13:02.084 --> 00:13:03.959
It was Dutch blood.

83
00:13:06.542 --> 00:13:08.459
It's our blood.

84
00:13:11.417 --> 00:13:12.834
This is our country.

85
00:13:14.292 --> 00:13:17.584
A country we conquered from the water.

86
00:13:17.709 --> 00:13:20.125
A country
where we earn our own happiness.

87
00:13:20.250 --> 00:13:23.709
By working hard.
in the villages and cities.

88
00:13:23.834 --> 00:13:25.875
In the ports and on the main land.

89
00:13:51.792 --> 00:13:56.750
Our freedom can only be protected if we are
willing to fight for freedom for others.

90
00:13:56.875 --> 00:14:03.250
That is why the Dutch lion
holds these seven arrows in his claw.

91
00:14:03.375 --> 00:14:05.000
That is what binds us.

92
00:14:13.334 --> 00:14:15.500
Your freedom is my freedom.

93
00:14:16.459 --> 00:14:19.792
I'll defend this freedom
until my last breath.

94
00:14:19.917 --> 00:14:23.042
Hear. hear.

95
00:14:54.375 --> 00:14:55.792
Gentlemen.

96
00:14:57.792 --> 00:15:00.209
Welcome home. - Lord mayor.

97
00:15:21.959 --> 00:15:24.500
Leave it. Neeltje.
I can do it myself.

98
00:15:28.417 --> 00:15:30.084
I said...

99
00:15:43.000 --> 00:15:44.667
Sorry. I look awful.

100
00:15:52.792 --> 00:15:56.042
Why aren't you in bed?
- I'm feeling better.

101
00:16:23.167 --> 00:16:26.875
How long will you be staying?
- For as long as you like.

102
00:16:29.542 --> 00:16:31.000
Honestly?

103
00:16:33.334 --> 00:16:35.834
I've told them to find someone else.

104
00:16:36.792 --> 00:16:38.459
What about the English?

105
00:16:39.959 --> 00:16:41.584
They don't pay enough.

106
00:16:46.542 --> 00:16:49.250
The English will be quiet for a while.

107
00:16:54.250 --> 00:16:56.584
I want to get on with our lives.

108
00:17:01.250 --> 00:17:04.250
We can finally extend
the vegetable garden.

109
00:17:05.750 --> 00:17:07.834
Great... As much as you like.

110
00:17:10.125 --> 00:17:12.917
I'm glad I ordered
an extra cask of beer.

111
00:17:18.667 --> 00:17:21.042
All those lost years.

112
00:17:25.209 --> 00:17:28.250
You were on your own
because I was away.

113
00:17:31.959 --> 00:17:35.167
Was it a boy or a girl?
- A girl.

114
00:17:48.959 --> 00:17:51.250
I'm staying with you now.

115
00:17:52.584 --> 00:17:55.000
I won't abandon you anymore.

116
00:18:23.209 --> 00:18:26.334
Good morning. - Slow down.

117
00:18:31.792 --> 00:18:34.750
Daddy. - Sleepyhead.

118
00:18:39.209 --> 00:18:42.709
We're awake now.
- I couldn't stop them.

119
00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:46.042
You stink. - Yes. of seaweed.

120
00:18:46.167 --> 00:18:49.709
Do I need a bath?
- There is a letter for you. daddy.

121
00:18:49.834 --> 00:18:52.542
What kind of letter?
- Come with us.

122
00:19:00.500 --> 00:19:01.917
Go ahead.

123
00:19:02.875 --> 00:19:04.292
Hello. son.

124
00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.167
There was a messenger.

125
00:19:12.292 --> 00:19:15.500
He had a fat horse.
- He came from The Hague.

126
00:19:15.625 --> 00:19:18.667
Open it. - Michiel.

127
00:19:19.459 --> 00:19:22.000
We're not aboard a ship.

128
00:19:30.875 --> 00:19:32.875
Look. it has a little hole.

129
00:19:37.667 --> 00:19:39.834
10 copies from this one.

130
00:19:52.250 --> 00:19:53.667
Tromp?

131
00:20:12.375 --> 00:20:15.875
Mr De Ruyter? This way. please.

132
00:20:32.417 --> 00:20:36.292
Mr De Ruyter. I've heard
so many good things about you.

133
00:20:36.417 --> 00:20:39.584
Really?
- You're the man to lead our fleet.

134
00:20:39.750 --> 00:20:42.709
You mean with Cornelis Tromp?
- No. under me.

135
00:20:42.834 --> 00:20:47.125
And not under Tromp?
- No. I want you. only you.

136
00:20:47.250 --> 00:20:49.292
As admiral?

137
00:20:49.417 --> 00:20:53.250
We need to rebuild
and modernize our fleet.

138
00:20:53.375 --> 00:20:55.500
I haven't served long enough.

139
00:20:55.625 --> 00:20:58.625
You have more experience than any other.
- As a sailor.

140
00:20:58.750 --> 00:21:01.625
No one will listen to me.
- We'll make them listen.

141
00:21:01.750 --> 00:21:04.625
I'm not of noble birth.
- Even better.

142
00:21:04.750 --> 00:21:07.000
Sailors are conservative.

143
00:21:07.125 --> 00:21:10.667
You can't just make anyone
admiral of the fleet.

144
00:21:10.792 --> 00:21:13.459
That's not how it works.
- Yes. it does.

145
00:21:13.542 --> 00:21:17.667
It's the 17th century. anything is
possible. - This is ridiculous.

146
00:21:20.375 --> 00:21:22.584
You were raised as an Orangist.

147
00:21:22.709 --> 00:21:26.292
Most men in Zeeland were.
- I'm not into politics.

148
00:21:26.459 --> 00:21:30.584
But that is an advantage.
sailors have to trust their admiral.

149
00:21:32.917 --> 00:21:36.584
De Ruyter. this is in our nations interest.

150
00:21:37.084 --> 00:21:39.334
I'm not setting sail again.

151
00:21:41.209 --> 00:21:44.709
In the last 15 years.
I've spent six months at home.

152
00:21:45.875 --> 00:21:47.834
You have to find someone else.

153
00:21:49.084 --> 00:21:52.125
Are you serious?
- Didn't I make myself clear?

154
00:21:52.375 --> 00:21:56.375
I won't find a better man than you.
- Of course you will.

155
00:21:56.500 --> 00:22:00.584
This is the 17th century.
anything is possible. Gentlemen.

156
00:22:04.792 --> 00:22:06.375
What a strange fellow.

157
00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:10.417
What a strange fellow.

158
00:22:12.167 --> 00:22:14.459
I guess we'll make Sir Obdam admiral.

159
00:22:18.834 --> 00:22:21.084
Damn it. admiral. what must we do?

160
00:22:22.667 --> 00:22:24.667
Retreat.

161
00:22:28.042 --> 00:22:30.542
We've lost 25 ships.

162
00:22:32.084 --> 00:22:36.417
3000 dead and 2000 men
taken prisoner by the English.

163
00:22:36.792 --> 00:22:39.542
Good men.
who fought for their country.

164
00:22:42.125 --> 00:22:43.750
Honest men.

165
00:22:44.750 --> 00:22:48.375
Who trusted the prime minister.
- Hear. hear.

166
00:22:48.500 --> 00:22:51.625
Who trusted him with their lives.

167
00:22:53.125 --> 00:22:57.167
Order.
- Do you think this will be the end of it?

168
00:22:59.084 --> 00:23:01.375
Is that honestly what you think?

169
00:23:07.334 --> 00:23:12.792
I'll tell you who is to blame.
That prime minister from Holland.

170
00:23:12.875 --> 00:23:15.292
And his republican friends.

171
00:23:16.042 --> 00:23:20.667
They should send him out to sea.
- This isn't your fault.

172
00:23:20.792 --> 00:23:24.750
The Spanish want our trade routes.
the Germans want to control our rivers.

173
00:23:24.917 --> 00:23:29.834
And the French can't wait to occupy
the Southern Netherlands.

174
00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:33.459
What are we going to do?

175
00:23:56.584 --> 00:23:57.875
Just go.

176
00:24:02.834 --> 00:24:05.250
I made you a promise.

177
00:24:05.375 --> 00:24:09.084
There is no use staying home
if there is no home left.

178
00:24:12.250 --> 00:24:14.292
Engel. come on.

179
00:24:17.292 --> 00:24:22.042
We need a strong leader
who is respected by other kingdoms.

180
00:24:22.292 --> 00:24:25.334
What do we do about it?
- The Prince of Orange...

181
00:24:25.459 --> 00:24:27.459
is nothing but a brat.

182
00:24:28.250 --> 00:24:32.875
A brat. Are we sure
that the Prince is a real man?

183
00:24:34.417 --> 00:24:38.792
I've been told he prefers ballet
over military strategy.

184
00:24:43.125 --> 00:24:47.375
Order. order. - Gentlemen.

185
00:24:47.500 --> 00:24:54.042
Let's keep it somewhat civilised.
What do you propose. regent Kievit?

186
00:24:55.959 --> 00:25:01.334
I propose we appoint
the honourable lord Cornelis Tromp...

187
00:25:01.459 --> 00:25:07.375
son of our greatest naval hero ever.
as our new admiral.

188
00:25:26.250 --> 00:25:29.417
Mr de Witt? - Mr Tromp.

189
00:25:29.542 --> 00:25:32.084
Do we have an appointment?
- No. we don't.

190
00:25:32.292 --> 00:25:34.792
I thought I'd speed things up.

191
00:25:41.875 --> 00:25:44.959
Since your father's funeral
I haven't had a chance...

192
00:25:45.084 --> 00:25:48.042
You're looking for someone
to replace my father.

193
00:25:48.250 --> 00:25:51.917
I'm looking into it.
- You probably don't realize...

194
00:25:52.042 --> 00:25:55.750
but the fleet will only accept
one man as their new admiral.

195
00:25:55.917 --> 00:25:57.459
And who is that?

196
00:25:59.000 --> 00:26:03.042
My blood is his blood.
The blood of Bestevaer.

197
00:26:03.792 --> 00:26:05.750
You might not understand.

198
00:26:05.834 --> 00:26:09.917
I understand the admiral
was a father figure to his men.

199
00:26:10.000 --> 00:26:13.500
But Bestevaer is a title of respect.

200
00:26:13.667 --> 00:26:16.625
You have to earn it.
it's not hereditary.

201
00:26:17.584 --> 00:26:19.750
I'm afraid it is. Mr de Witt.

202
00:26:19.917 --> 00:26:24.084
Heroes father heroes.
that's how sailors see it.

203
00:26:24.292 --> 00:26:27.750
And that. Mr de Witt.
will never change.

204
00:26:32.000 --> 00:26:34.875
You're still thinking about De Ruyter?

205
00:26:34.959 --> 00:26:37.709
Why not invite him to dinner?

206
00:26:37.792 --> 00:26:41.792
Johan. he's stubborn.
- Invite his wife too. this time.

207
00:27:02.625 --> 00:27:06.709
Mr. and Mrs. De Ruyter. welcome. Come in.

208
00:27:14.125 --> 00:27:16.959
Was it a long trip. De Ruyter?

209
00:27:18.584 --> 00:27:20.667
From Vlissingen to The Hague.

210
00:27:20.750 --> 00:27:24.917
Of course.
- Darling. don't just stand there.

211
00:27:25.000 --> 00:27:28.667
Won't you offer our guests a drink?
- Yes.

212
00:27:28.792 --> 00:27:32.459
You didn't tell me they have a baby.
- My wife. Wendela.

213
00:27:32.584 --> 00:27:34.750
What a cutie.

214
00:27:34.875 --> 00:27:37.209
Excuse me. - What for?

215
00:27:37.375 --> 00:27:40.959
She is a cutie.
I'll show you round the house.

216
00:27:41.125 --> 00:27:44.709
Wine?
Or do sailors only drink beer?

217
00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:49.125
Girls.
Why don't you show us around?

218
00:27:56.375 --> 00:28:00.292
We need larger ships with more cannons.

219
00:28:00.375 --> 00:28:02.292
Larger ships. fine.

220
00:28:03.625 --> 00:28:06.125
They must be agile
and have a shallow draught.

221
00:28:06.292 --> 00:28:08.625
Merchant ships are of no use to me.

222
00:28:08.709 --> 00:28:13.250
I'll arrange it. What else?
- Better pay for the crew.

223
00:28:15.584 --> 00:28:17.084
Higher wages?

224
00:28:17.250 --> 00:28:20.334
If they die.
they leave a family behind.

225
00:28:22.000 --> 00:28:23.542
Consider it done.

226
00:28:23.667 --> 00:28:26.417
Doesn't the parliament
have to approve. first?

227
00:28:26.542 --> 00:28:28.417
Leave that to me.

228
00:28:29.750 --> 00:28:33.750
Each winter. the fleet lies at anchor.
It's a waste of time.

229
00:28:33.834 --> 00:28:34.875
I agree.

230
00:28:35.000 --> 00:28:38.792
If I were admiral.
I'd train the crew in winter.

231
00:28:38.875 --> 00:28:42.250
Exactly.
And that costs money. too.

232
00:28:42.375 --> 00:28:45.667
Carry on. What else?
- The sea-battles?

233
00:28:45.792 --> 00:28:50.084
In battle now. it's every ship for itself.
It's total chaos.

234
00:28:50.292 --> 00:28:55.750
Organisation is key.
- You mentioned sign flags in the past.

235
00:28:55.834 --> 00:28:58.334
The English have been using them
for years.

236
00:28:58.459 --> 00:29:01.459
But their system is too limited.

237
00:29:02.792 --> 00:29:05.959
The ladies are chatting.
Mr prime minister?

238
00:29:06.084 --> 00:29:09.084
Allow me to introduce my brother.
Cornelis.

239
00:29:09.250 --> 00:29:14.417
Tell us about the system we developed. - Our
system? I happen to have it right here.

240
00:29:18.750 --> 00:29:21.125
We disagreed about the colours.

241
00:29:21.292 --> 00:29:24.750
Johan felt we were using too much orange.
- A bit too much.

242
00:29:25.750 --> 00:29:30.042
So. what do you say. De Ruyter?
Are you going to do this job?

243
00:29:30.250 --> 00:29:32.292
Or do you have more demands?

244
00:29:36.417 --> 00:29:40.917
I. Michiel Adriaenszoon de Ruyter...

245
00:29:41.042 --> 00:29:44.167
The English have
a limited flag system.

246
00:29:44.334 --> 00:29:47.959
We're expanding our flag system
with all these codes.

247
00:29:48.084 --> 00:29:55.625
Swear allegiance to the Republic
of the United Netherlands.

248
00:29:55.750 --> 00:30:00.792
And then change the signal. Only
these 6 bow cannons are a problem.

249
00:30:00.875 --> 00:30:04.084
We tack as fast as we can
and then...

250
00:30:25.500 --> 00:30:30.917
We fire everything we have
on the port side on these ships here.

251
00:30:31.042 --> 00:30:32.334
Fire.

252
00:30:33.459 --> 00:30:38.042
Cool and reload. Come on. Faster.

253
00:30:42.125 --> 00:30:45.084
And? - We're here.

254
00:30:46.500 --> 00:30:48.084
Wait.

255
00:30:49.834 --> 00:30:55.709
Do you really think I look all right?
- You're the Prince of Orange.

256
00:30:55.792 --> 00:30:58.125
All of the Netherlands loves you.

257
00:31:07.584 --> 00:31:10.959
Huzzah. huzzah. huzzah.

258
00:31:15.500 --> 00:31:18.792
Your Highness. - Prime minister.

259
00:31:18.875 --> 00:31:22.750
May I introduce gentlemen De Witt.
Tromp and our new admiral?

260
00:31:22.875 --> 00:31:25.875
Admiral De Ruyter. our great sea hero.

261
00:31:26.000 --> 00:31:29.500
You can't imagine
how glad I am to meet you.

262
00:31:29.625 --> 00:31:33.875
I want to hear all about your travels
to Africa and your escape from France.

263
00:31:33.959 --> 00:31:36.917
This is my wife. Anna.
- Your Highness.

264
00:31:37.000 --> 00:31:38.500
Fascinating.

265
00:31:39.792 --> 00:31:41.584
Fascinating.

266
00:31:46.417 --> 00:31:53.042
I promise to do my utmost
to truly follow...

267
00:31:53.292 --> 00:31:56.042
the instructions and orders...

268
00:31:56.292 --> 00:32:02.875
in regards to my position as admiral
- the Supreme Commander of the Fleet.

269
00:32:33.459 --> 00:32:37.125
You're very brave to be here Your Highness.
surrounded by these republicans.

270
00:32:38.125 --> 00:32:41.584
The English fleet has set sail.
- Four squadrons.

271
00:32:41.667 --> 00:32:44.542
They're blocking our merchant ships.

272
00:32:44.667 --> 00:32:48.000
We have to take action
before our goods are lost.

273
00:33:09.375 --> 00:33:13.125
One. two. all together...

274
00:33:13.292 --> 00:33:15.834
One. two. all together...

275
00:33:23.000 --> 00:33:28.125
One. two. all together...

276
00:33:29.334 --> 00:33:31.500
Work those ropes.

277
00:33:31.584 --> 00:33:33.875
Get that wind in the sails.

278
00:33:40.042 --> 00:33:42.792
Render those ropes further.

279
00:33:44.542 --> 00:33:46.292
Come on.

280
00:33:49.959 --> 00:33:52.375
One. two. all together...

281
00:34:12.167 --> 00:34:16.042
If the wind turns. the rear squadron
sails around them.

282
00:34:16.167 --> 00:34:20.750
So I have to keep an eye on your flags
while I'm surrounded by flying canon balls?

283
00:34:20.834 --> 00:34:23.750
Just give me an extra 150 men.
- No. it'll be chaos.

284
00:34:23.834 --> 00:34:26.792
The English have more ships.
bigger guns.

285
00:34:26.834 --> 00:34:30.917
We stick to the plan. Or do we want
another defeat like Lowestoft?

286
00:34:32.709 --> 00:34:36.375
We must make sure
we're well-organised.

287
00:34:36.500 --> 00:34:40.750
Good. we'll do it your way.
You stubborn Zeelander.

288
00:34:41.834 --> 00:34:44.875
Are you prepared to die
for the fatherland?

289
00:34:50.792 --> 00:34:53.750
To the fatherland.

290
00:35:05.500 --> 00:35:07.417
Wonderful.

291
00:35:07.542 --> 00:35:11.292
God bless you.
- Half a turn to port.

292
00:35:11.417 --> 00:35:14.500
Half a turn to port.

293
00:35:21.542 --> 00:35:24.625
What's going on? - Gout.

294
00:35:24.750 --> 00:35:26.584
Am I in the way? - Not at all.

295
00:35:26.750 --> 00:35:28.667
A perfect target for the English.

296
00:35:34.542 --> 00:35:38.417
The Royal Charles.
Unsinkable. or so they say.

297
00:35:38.542 --> 00:35:40.709
All ships are unsinkable. Jan.

298
00:35:42.959 --> 00:35:44.709
Until they sink.

299
00:36:26.667 --> 00:36:29.875
Signal: In line.
- You mean this one. sir?

300
00:36:30.000 --> 00:36:31.500
Put it up.

301
00:36:55.834 --> 00:36:59.792
It's impressive. - You'll see.
it'll be every ship for itself.

302
00:37:12.625 --> 00:37:14.542
Captain. - Yes. sir.

303
00:37:14.667 --> 00:37:20.042
Vanguard closer to the wind.
- Vanguard. luff up.

304
00:37:23.000 --> 00:37:24.792
Ready to go about. now.

305
00:37:25.917 --> 00:37:30.917
Pull up the mizzen sail.

306
00:37:31.042 --> 00:37:35.292
Come on. keep pulling those braces.

307
00:38:19.417 --> 00:38:23.875
Load starboard.
- Load starboard.

308
00:38:24.000 --> 00:38:26.917
Do you want me to call your mother?

309
00:38:27.042 --> 00:38:31.542
Get to work. Faster. - Faster.

310
00:38:44.000 --> 00:38:46.292
Mainsail halyard.

311
00:38:55.750 --> 00:38:59.334
Come on. load. Faster.

312
00:39:10.917 --> 00:39:13.459
Faster. - Keep it in the wind.

313
00:39:52.125 --> 00:39:53.917
Brace yourselves.

314
00:39:55.042 --> 00:39:57.292
Wait. - Wait.

315
00:39:58.709 --> 00:40:00.334
Wait.

316
00:40:01.417 --> 00:40:05.042
Everybody wait.

317
00:40:05.334 --> 00:40:08.875
Jibs forward. - Luff up.

318
00:40:12.667 --> 00:40:15.042
Wait.

319
00:40:29.459 --> 00:40:31.084
Attention.

320
00:40:57.959 --> 00:40:59.000
Admiral?

321
00:41:02.875 --> 00:41:07.500
Trim the lines.

322
00:41:11.417 --> 00:41:12.834
Fire.

323
00:41:47.167 --> 00:41:50.084
Let him be.
Get back. Keep firing.

324
00:42:02.084 --> 00:42:07.084
Pull up the mizzen sail. Luff up.

325
00:42:07.167 --> 00:42:11.584
Come on. get going. - Come on.

326
00:42:11.709 --> 00:42:14.167
They need to reload faster. Come on.

327
00:42:44.084 --> 00:42:47.542
You're too slow.
- Why is it taking so long?

328
00:42:47.625 --> 00:42:50.750
Faster. or you're going overboard.

329
00:42:55.125 --> 00:42:57.417
Speed it up. Come on. boy.

330
00:42:57.584 --> 00:42:59.625
I need to shit. - No shitting.

331
00:42:59.750 --> 00:43:04.000
Reload the cannon.
You can have that shit later.

332
00:43:05.542 --> 00:43:09.709
Come on. Reload the cannons.
Reload like lightning.

333
00:43:09.834 --> 00:43:12.500
Come on. reload.

334
00:43:14.292 --> 00:43:20.834
Get back to work. Get back to that
cannon. Are you sleeping or what?

335
00:43:22.625 --> 00:43:25.459
Captain. how is the rear?

336
00:43:25.584 --> 00:43:29.500
The English are on lee side.
- Middle squadron luff up.

337
00:43:29.625 --> 00:43:32.000
Gijs. middle squadron luff up.

338
00:43:44.334 --> 00:43:48.375
Hold the lines.
- Get that wind in the sails.

339
00:43:48.500 --> 00:43:51.792
Port. Keep going.

340
00:44:04.459 --> 00:44:09.209
Reload the cannons. starboard. port.

341
00:44:10.334 --> 00:44:12.959
Look. that Englishman is mine.

342
00:44:13.042 --> 00:44:16.375
Two points port.
- We need to stay in line.

343
00:44:16.500 --> 00:44:20.084
Two points port.
- But the signal from De Ruyter.

344
00:44:28.625 --> 00:44:30.584
All right. come about.

345
00:44:30.709 --> 00:44:36.167
Come about. Brace the sails.

346
00:44:46.750 --> 00:44:50.542
Load port cannons.

347
00:44:52.209 --> 00:44:53.792
Cover.

348
00:44:55.500 --> 00:44:57.542
Fire.

349
00:45:14.250 --> 00:45:16.125
Keep that head in the wind.

350
00:45:16.792 --> 00:45:20.000
De Ruyter's strategy is not going to work.

351
00:45:22.375 --> 00:45:24.792
And we're the ones under fire.

352
00:45:28.167 --> 00:45:31.000
Load port cannons.

353
00:45:34.125 --> 00:45:36.500
What are you doing? Get in position.

354
00:45:36.625 --> 00:45:38.459
Load port cannons.

355
00:45:58.042 --> 00:46:00.500
Grappling hooks.

356
00:46:00.625 --> 00:46:04.834
A portion of rum for the man who puts
the most English to the sword.

357
00:47:47.792 --> 00:47:50.459
Do you want a hug from De Witt?

358
00:48:26.042 --> 00:48:32.000
Victory is ours. A cheer for Tromp.

359
00:48:33.709 --> 00:48:37.625
A cheer for Piet's cannons.

360
00:48:37.709 --> 00:48:40.542
A cheer for our captain.

361
00:48:41.584 --> 00:48:46.709
And three cheers for our admiral.

362
00:49:30.917 --> 00:49:34.292
Can His Highness receive me?
- Certainly.

363
00:49:53.459 --> 00:49:56.084
Your Highness. lord Kievit.

364
00:49:57.959 --> 00:50:01.084
Our fleet has given
the English a beating.

365
00:50:01.250 --> 00:50:04.667
So De Ruyter is as good as they say.

366
00:50:04.750 --> 00:50:08.667
Quite a victory for Johan de Witt.
- For the Netherlands.

367
00:50:08.750 --> 00:50:10.750
Gentlemen? - Of course.

368
00:50:11.875 --> 00:50:14.125
While I stand by doing nothing.

369
00:50:14.292 --> 00:50:18.167
All my relatives and friends
are kings or important people.

370
00:50:18.334 --> 00:50:23.584
Even those Habsburger simpletons.
with their in-bred minds.

371
00:50:24.750 --> 00:50:28.792
Why doesn't anyone take
the Prince of Orange seriously?

372
00:50:28.917 --> 00:50:32.709
You can play a decisive role.
If I may be so bold.

373
00:50:35.917 --> 00:50:39.375
You're the cousin of the English king.

374
00:51:32.792 --> 00:51:38.959
So. 7200. 8400. 10.800
amounts to a total of 5.14 percent.

375
00:51:39.084 --> 00:51:43.084
As I was saying. we can calculate
average life expectancy.

376
00:51:43.250 --> 00:51:45.709
And adapt the price of annuities.

377
00:51:45.792 --> 00:51:49.042
If my calculations are correct...
- They are.

378
00:51:50.125 --> 00:51:52.334
Indeed they are.

379
00:51:52.459 --> 00:51:57.125
The 7.14 percent the State
is paying out now. is far too high.

380
00:51:57.292 --> 00:51:59.709
So. we can save a lot of money.

381
00:51:59.792 --> 00:52:03.334
Money the State can use
to build more ships.

382
00:52:08.750 --> 00:52:14.417
But. must people die earlier or later
to make this work?

383
00:52:14.542 --> 00:52:16.959
Exactly. it's not clear.

384
00:52:18.375 --> 00:52:20.542
It's not clear.

385
00:52:20.667 --> 00:52:25.000
I'll explain one more time
what the percentages mean.

386
00:52:26.542 --> 00:52:30.125
Why earlier?
- Gentlemen. please excuse us.

387
00:52:32.709 --> 00:52:35.750
Didn't you say
you could explain it to a child?

388
00:52:39.125 --> 00:52:42.459
The English have sailed again. sir.

389
00:52:43.542 --> 00:52:47.709
De Ruyter will have to get ready.
- Sounds like a good idea.

390
00:53:09.417 --> 00:53:10.750
Thanks. guys.

391
00:53:28.042 --> 00:53:31.000
That goes in the kitchen.
and that one.

392
00:53:31.125 --> 00:53:33.459
And that one goes to the study.

393
00:53:33.584 --> 00:53:36.667
Are you sure? - Yes.

394
00:53:36.750 --> 00:53:40.000
Need a hand? - Michiel.

395
00:53:40.167 --> 00:53:43.542
Aren't you sailing tomorrow?
- Yes. with the first tide.

396
00:53:43.667 --> 00:53:46.959
I thought we'd have dinner together.
- Daddy.

397
00:53:49.709 --> 00:53:52.209
I have my own room.
- You live here too?

398
00:53:52.334 --> 00:53:55.959
We have our own box bed.
- Go ahead. I'll be right in.

399
00:53:56.125 --> 00:54:00.292
The admiralty suggested a larger house.
but this is near the harbour.

400
00:54:00.417 --> 00:54:02.709
As long as you live here.

401
00:54:04.917 --> 00:54:06.709
Dad. are you coming?

402
00:54:17.375 --> 00:54:21.250
Dad. this is our bed.
- Look at that.

403
00:54:22.292 --> 00:54:25.042
No boots in bed.

404
00:54:26.125 --> 00:54:28.417
You sound just like your mother.

405
00:54:30.125 --> 00:54:32.584
What are you doing?

406
00:54:42.500 --> 00:54:46.375
VOC? Can I have a look?
- Go ahead.

407
00:54:54.084 --> 00:54:59.542
Flooded cellar?
- I'll take the supplier off my list.

408
00:54:59.667 --> 00:55:02.459
Don't bother. - What?

409
00:55:03.750 --> 00:55:07.709
You can't do this.
I've supplied the fleet for years.

410
00:55:07.792 --> 00:55:10.334
Why do we get the worst grain?

411
00:55:11.417 --> 00:55:14.125
Or do you supply this muck
to the VOC too?

412
00:55:17.167 --> 00:55:18.709
Is there a problem?

413
00:55:21.584 --> 00:55:25.375
You don't get better grain
for your republican pals.

414
00:55:28.292 --> 00:55:31.834
Who does he think he is?
We'll find someone else.

415
00:55:33.959 --> 00:55:36.375
What? - That was the third one.

416
00:55:38.375 --> 00:55:40.084
Why didn't you tell me?

417
00:55:40.292 --> 00:55:43.334
Because you're busy
saving the country.

418
00:57:50.459 --> 00:57:52.542
Come and join me.

419
00:59:41.625 --> 00:59:43.000
Are you all right?

420
00:59:44.000 --> 00:59:45.500
Leave me. I want to be alone.

421
00:59:53.125 --> 00:59:56.792
Faster. guys. - Come about.

422
00:59:57.792 --> 01:00:01.584
Keep it tight.

423
01:00:06.459 --> 01:00:08.459
What are they doing? - Gijs.

424
01:00:08.875 --> 01:00:13.417
They try to cut us off.
Take the signals to the front now.

425
01:00:13.542 --> 01:00:17.459
Tack over port.
- Ready to come about.

426
01:00:17.542 --> 01:00:19.709
Full about now.

427
01:00:47.709 --> 01:00:50.334
Get to work on the lower decks.

428
01:00:51.709 --> 01:00:54.292
Keep it up.

429
01:00:58.584 --> 01:01:02.875
Follow those two ships there.
- We'll break the line. Tromp.

430
01:01:03.000 --> 01:01:06.709
Sod off with your line.
those ships are mine.

431
01:01:06.834 --> 01:01:10.500
Four points to starboard.
- Michiel ordered it.

432
01:01:11.459 --> 01:01:14.750
Who is the highest ranking officer?
Come about.

433
01:01:15.834 --> 01:01:19.750
Four points to starboard.
Come about.

434
01:01:56.584 --> 01:02:00.334
Where is Tromp?
- He has broken line.

435
01:02:03.125 --> 01:02:05.375
Cannons ready?

436
01:02:20.042 --> 01:02:21.292
Fire.

437
01:02:37.959 --> 01:02:39.542
Damn it.

438
01:02:41.334 --> 01:02:43.042
God damn it.

439
01:03:36.250 --> 01:03:40.167
Michiel. they're surrounding us.
- Where is Tromp?

440
01:03:49.917 --> 01:03:51.542
Keep pulling.

441
01:04:23.709 --> 01:04:27.250
I'm sorry. admiral.
- Lie still. don't move.

442
01:04:28.084 --> 01:04:29.917
Admiral?

443
01:04:32.125 --> 01:04:33.959
It doesn't hurt at all.

444
01:05:07.959 --> 01:05:13.125
You're the rock on which I build. the
future awaiting me. my highest good.

445
01:05:13.250 --> 01:05:17.542
Seventeen killed on the gunners' deck.
All of them brought up.

446
01:05:18.792 --> 01:05:23.834
You're the rock on which I build. the
future awaiting me. my highest good.

447
01:05:23.917 --> 01:05:25.000
Hang in there.

448
01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:55.000
I've lost twenty ships.

449
01:05:55.084 --> 01:05:58.417
Who was in command?
- I gave you an order.

450
01:05:58.584 --> 01:06:02.292
So court-martial me.
- Get back into that longboat.

451
01:06:02.417 --> 01:06:07.709
Don't set foot on my ship or on any
other ship in this fleet. ever again.

452
01:06:07.792 --> 01:06:11.417
You are relieved of your duties
as of now. so piss off.

453
01:06:11.584 --> 01:06:15.959
Leave it to the court-martial.
- You disgrace the name of Tromp.

454
01:06:18.792 --> 01:06:21.084
Leave my father out of this.

455
01:06:23.334 --> 01:06:26.000
He'd be ashamed of you.

456
01:06:35.125 --> 01:06:37.084
Michiel. you can't do this.

457
01:06:37.209 --> 01:06:40.667
You want to be dishonourably
discharged as well?

458
01:06:43.959 --> 01:06:45.625
Come on. back to work.

459
01:06:45.792 --> 01:06:49.167
Get down there
and pick up those cannons.

460
01:07:28.500 --> 01:07:34.834
Master Buat is a loyal rittmeister.
You're executing such a loyal servant?

461
01:07:34.959 --> 01:07:39.334
Who is he serving? He went to
the king of England behind my back.

462
01:07:39.417 --> 01:07:42.709
In the national interest.
- Your interest.

463
01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:47.792
I've seen enough.

464
01:08:21.292 --> 01:08:25.750
I shouldn't have lost my temper
with Tromp.

465
01:08:27.334 --> 01:08:31.459
He is the vice-admiral. after all.
- He deserved it.

466
01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:37.792
Stay down or I'll put this
you know where.

467
01:08:40.167 --> 01:08:43.959
It's just a cold. - Malaria.

468
01:08:48.959 --> 01:08:51.084
Where is the patient?
- Upstairs.

469
01:08:51.167 --> 01:08:53.667
De Ruyter? - That's Johan.

470
01:08:56.084 --> 01:08:58.084
Do what you have to do.

471
01:09:00.709 --> 01:09:04.875
We haven't heard anything from the English.
- They've run out of money.

472
01:09:06.417 --> 01:09:09.917
So why won't they negotiate peace?

473
01:09:10.917 --> 01:09:15.125
They hope we're afraid of the French.
We can't afford two wars.

474
01:09:15.209 --> 01:09:19.584
The French? Are they a real threat?
- No. but the Orangists are.

475
01:09:19.709 --> 01:09:22.709
They say I'm too weak
to force a peace treaty.

476
01:09:25.042 --> 01:09:28.042
You must force the English
to their knees.

477
01:09:30.875 --> 01:09:32.709
You have a plan.

478
01:09:35.167 --> 01:09:37.375
It's not without risk.

479
01:09:37.625 --> 01:09:40.667
You know the English fleet
is in Chatham.

480
01:09:40.834 --> 01:09:43.959
With the right wind
it's only a two day sail inland.

481
01:09:44.084 --> 01:09:47.792
You want to sail up the Medway?
- Yes. What?

482
01:09:47.917 --> 01:09:50.459
Is it crazy? Would nobody do it?

483
01:09:50.667 --> 01:09:53.625
Sail through their chains?

484
01:09:53.750 --> 01:09:57.959
You must be desperate.
- I know it's a lot to ask for.

485
01:09:58.042 --> 01:10:02.042
Not now. get out of here.
- Sorry. dad.

486
01:10:07.875 --> 01:10:11.209
What about those sea soldiers
you're training?

487
01:10:11.334 --> 01:10:15.000
What do you call them?
- Marines.

488
01:10:15.875 --> 01:10:18.084
Is this a good time to test them?

489
01:10:19.625 --> 01:10:21.042
It's a bad time.

490
01:10:22.334 --> 01:10:25.042
Not even men like that
can be asked to...

491
01:10:34.250 --> 01:10:38.334
Forget about it. it's a silly plan.
Really silly.

492
01:11:02.209 --> 01:11:05.042
Which one do you want? That one?

493
01:11:08.334 --> 01:11:10.250
Thank you. - Bye.

494
01:11:13.959 --> 01:11:15.625
Hi. darling. - Dad's up.

495
01:11:18.459 --> 01:11:20.000
What are you doing?

496
01:11:21.250 --> 01:11:23.167
Try to understand.

497
01:11:23.292 --> 01:11:26.167
If I don't go...
- Where are you going?

498
01:11:27.250 --> 01:11:29.084
Can't you tell me?

499
01:11:31.000 --> 01:11:32.750
That's a first.

500
01:11:52.917 --> 01:11:56.667
The Lord bless you and keep you.

501
01:11:56.792 --> 01:12:01.000
The Lord make his face shine on you
and be gracious to you.

502
01:12:01.084 --> 01:12:04.709
The Lord turn his face toward you...

503
01:12:04.834 --> 01:12:08.375
and give you peace. - Amen.

504
01:12:14.792 --> 01:12:18.500
Thank you. my thoughts
are with admiral De Ruyter.

505
01:12:18.625 --> 01:12:20.042
Thank you.

506
01:12:25.625 --> 01:12:26.875
For my husband.

507
01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:31.084
I don't know...
- You know where they are.

508
01:12:31.209 --> 01:12:34.709
For my husband. - For my son.

509
01:13:39.792 --> 01:13:41.917
Where is Michiel?

510
01:13:42.042 --> 01:13:45.459
These women have no idea
where their husbands are.

511
01:13:45.667 --> 01:13:47.750
Johan must know.

512
01:13:49.834 --> 01:13:53.042
Johan. I'm sorry to disturb you.

513
01:13:53.792 --> 01:13:57.292
Anna is here. Where is the fleet?
Where is Michiel?

514
01:13:57.959 --> 01:14:00.875
I don't know. I can't reach them.

515
01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:04.042
Tell her that yourself.

516
01:14:08.792 --> 01:14:10.375
Come on in.

517
01:14:24.209 --> 01:14:27.375
They're on the Medway.
- Heading for London?

518
01:14:58.125 --> 01:14:59.709
It's time.

519
01:15:00.750 --> 01:15:04.917
Gentlemen. the people
are counting on you.

520
01:15:07.334 --> 01:15:08.792
Over to you.

521
01:15:10.792 --> 01:15:13.709
Men. into the longboats.

522
01:15:41.917 --> 01:15:43.417
Down.

523
01:15:45.709 --> 01:15:46.750
Up.

524
01:15:49.042 --> 01:15:50.625
Forward.

525
01:16:36.167 --> 01:16:38.792
Those brothers De Witt.

526
01:17:42.625 --> 01:17:44.084
Watch out.

527
01:18:10.375 --> 01:18:13.750
It's a shame to burn that one.

528
01:18:17.375 --> 01:18:20.167
Members of the State.
I present to you...

529
01:18:20.292 --> 01:18:23.125
the stern carving
of the Royal Charles.

530
01:18:34.792 --> 01:18:37.500
You didn't expect that one. eh?

531
01:18:57.375 --> 01:19:02.667
Charles II has accepted our terms.
The peace treaty will be signed in Breda.

532
01:19:04.417 --> 01:19:07.084
Van Ginneken. let me embrace you.

533
01:19:57.334 --> 01:19:59.084
I can't do it.

534
01:19:59.667 --> 01:20:02.500
Delicious. It looks fantastic.

535
01:20:02.709 --> 01:20:04.125
Well.

536
01:20:05.125 --> 01:20:07.042
I propose a toast. - Again?

537
01:20:07.125 --> 01:20:10.125
To peace.
- We've already toasted to that.

538
01:20:10.209 --> 01:20:14.042
To us.
- That's much better. To us.

539
01:20:14.167 --> 01:20:19.875
Can we go and play now?
- Yes. go and play. Quickly now.

540
01:20:20.000 --> 01:20:21.417
Be careful.

541
01:20:21.750 --> 01:20:23.375
Not too fast.

542
01:20:28.792 --> 01:20:32.167
What? Should I have proposed
a toast to the Prince?

543
01:20:32.292 --> 01:20:36.125
This peace won't last.
- It's politics. One day at a time.

544
01:20:36.250 --> 01:20:40.084
Michiel is worried about the French.
- You mean you are.

545
01:20:40.209 --> 01:20:44.625
So. everything is fine?
The French are building up their troops.

546
01:20:44.750 --> 01:20:47.292
Rumours. - Persistent rumours.

547
01:20:47.459 --> 01:20:51.084
So you want to expand the army?
- We should have done that already.

548
01:20:51.125 --> 01:20:55.959
The army is full of Orangists. How many
batallions will you give the Prince?

549
01:20:56.084 --> 01:20:59.417
You're asking for a civil war.
- Cornelis means...

550
01:20:59.625 --> 01:21:03.709
I think I know what he means.
Damn it.

551
01:21:05.542 --> 01:21:07.084
Idiot.

552
01:21:09.542 --> 01:21:12.375
Can't we just enjoy ourselves
for once?

553
01:21:12.542 --> 01:21:17.500
We're at peace with the English. The
republicans hold a stable majority.

554
01:21:17.709 --> 01:21:21.209
In the meeting hall.
- Useless when the French invade.

555
01:21:21.292 --> 01:21:24.417
They never will.
- The people are scared.

556
01:21:24.500 --> 01:21:28.250
That's silly of them.
- It's all my men talk about. too.

557
01:21:28.375 --> 01:21:32.417
Diplomacy. Michiel.
diplomacy is the future of warfare.

558
01:21:32.542 --> 01:21:35.292
The people don't understand diplomacy.

559
01:21:38.750 --> 01:21:43.167
I can't adapt my policy to people
who understand less than we do.

560
01:21:48.125 --> 01:21:51.500
Come on. gentlemen.
we're having a party.

561
01:21:53.125 --> 01:21:56.084
I'm going to dance
with my fantastic wife.

562
01:22:03.292 --> 01:22:06.292
You heard the man.
we're having a party.

563
01:22:11.209 --> 01:22:13.209
Mr Chairman...

564
01:22:14.292 --> 01:22:18.417
they say that Louis
is gathering 100.000 troops.

565
01:22:18.542 --> 01:22:22.125
They say. they say...
Who says so? Who?

566
01:22:22.292 --> 01:22:27.542
Mr Van Ginneken has it easy with
his district behind the defence lines.

567
01:22:27.709 --> 01:22:29.667
Order.

568
01:22:32.375 --> 01:22:33.917
Mr Chairman...

569
01:22:34.042 --> 01:22:38.375
we've been paying huge taxes.

570
01:22:38.500 --> 01:22:41.375
And what are we getting in return?

571
01:22:41.500 --> 01:22:45.334
Give up the south and perhaps
Louis will levy less taxes.

572
01:22:45.459 --> 01:22:49.167
Would you say that to my face?
- I certainly would.

573
01:22:49.334 --> 01:22:52.709
I'll repeat it to your face:
Give up the south.

574
01:22:54.000 --> 01:22:56.709
Order. order.

575
01:22:57.417 --> 01:22:59.209
Gentlemen.

576
01:22:59.334 --> 01:23:03.625
Louis can mass all the troops
he wants. but he can't attack us.

577
01:23:04.417 --> 01:23:09.500
He'll face the Swedes and the English.
We have it in black and white.

578
01:23:09.917 --> 01:23:14.917
What if Charles breaks his word?
- We are on good terms with England.

579
01:23:17.542 --> 01:23:20.459
Right honourable member Kievit...

580
01:23:21.167 --> 01:23:24.709
I hope you're not suffering
from sleepless nights?

581
01:23:26.917 --> 01:23:30.250
I'd sleep better
if the Prince were king.

582
01:23:30.375 --> 01:23:34.417
Only then we know for sure
that Charles won't betray us.

583
01:23:48.000 --> 01:23:53.209
You're responsible for the civil war
in this country. You. Mr De Witt.

584
01:23:53.334 --> 01:23:55.000
Damn you.

585
01:25:21.917 --> 01:25:25.584
The French are in Maastricht
with 100.000 soldiers.

586
01:25:25.709 --> 01:25:29.084
And Louis XIV is there himself.
- Not bad for us.

587
01:25:29.959 --> 01:25:33.917
Not bad for us?
What do you mean?

588
01:25:34.000 --> 01:25:36.709
Do you realise
what is about to happen?

589
01:25:36.834 --> 01:25:40.084
Your Highness can save the country.

590
01:25:40.167 --> 01:25:43.917
And become supreme commander.
- And king.

591
01:25:44.042 --> 01:25:49.334
Charles has forged a deal with Louis.
- Charles has agreed not to interfere.

592
01:25:51.209 --> 01:25:52.959
Don't you get it?

593
01:25:54.209 --> 01:25:58.334
And you don't get it either?
You don't get it either.

594
01:25:59.542 --> 01:26:03.334
Do you think Charles
would give our country to Louis?

595
01:26:08.250 --> 01:26:10.500
The English will invade Holland.

596
01:26:25.125 --> 01:26:27.125
Go on. I'll finish this.

597
01:26:29.334 --> 01:26:31.167
Have you heard the news?

598
01:26:31.250 --> 01:26:35.167
The French are at the border.
- The English near the coast.

599
01:26:35.292 --> 01:26:36.542
And that's not all.

600
01:26:36.709 --> 01:26:40.459
The bishops of Cologne and Münster
are joining in.

601
01:26:40.584 --> 01:26:44.709
They've divided our country.
everyone gets a piece of the pie.

602
01:26:45.667 --> 01:26:47.584
It's not just about destroying our fleet.

603
01:26:47.750 --> 01:26:52.250
They want to land near The Hague
with a huge number of troops.

604
01:26:52.375 --> 01:26:56.334
You must stop them.
Our land army won't survive it.

605
01:26:56.459 --> 01:26:58.792
You're our only hope. Michiel.

606
01:26:58.959 --> 01:27:02.834
Don't let them turn us
into English and French provinces.

607
01:27:08.917 --> 01:27:12.917
Has it got worse again?
- I could do with some fresh air.

608
01:27:13.000 --> 01:27:15.959
It's better you stay with him.

609
01:27:17.792 --> 01:27:19.167
Thank you.

610
01:27:30.167 --> 01:27:32.750
I should never have weakened our army.

611
01:27:38.167 --> 01:27:40.459
If only I had fixed this earlier.

612
01:27:44.792 --> 01:27:47.917
This country has been blessed
to have you.

613
01:27:48.042 --> 01:27:50.417
No one could've predicted this.

614
01:27:54.167 --> 01:27:56.542
To the admiralty.

615
01:28:00.542 --> 01:28:03.209
Go on.
- Long live the prime minister.

616
01:28:03.334 --> 01:28:06.417
What was that?
You did not cheer for our Prince?

617
01:28:16.042 --> 01:28:20.167
Are you on Charles II's pay roll?
Do you work for the English?

618
01:28:21.167 --> 01:28:25.834
I suggest you leave this sailor alone.
We'll be needing him.

619
01:28:25.959 --> 01:28:27.709
Get lost.

620
01:28:28.875 --> 01:28:32.209
Aren't you brave? Losers.

621
01:28:33.334 --> 01:28:37.084
You're going back to Vlissingen.
- No. I'm staying here.

622
01:28:37.167 --> 01:28:40.084
You're so stubborn.
- Look who's talking.

623
01:28:40.167 --> 01:28:42.042
Engel. get inside.

624
01:28:45.500 --> 01:28:46.917
I can do this myself.

625
01:28:49.125 --> 01:28:52.917
I'll take care of him.
you take the girls to Vlissingen.

626
01:28:53.042 --> 01:28:55.000
Who says it's safer there?

627
01:28:55.084 --> 01:28:59.084
They think we're traitors
who work for the republicans.

628
01:30:11.250 --> 01:30:12.959
Eat your vegetables.

629
01:30:13.959 --> 01:30:18.167
I could hardly get through.
- Eat up before it gets cold.

630
01:30:19.167 --> 01:30:22.084
There are more and more of them.

631
01:30:22.167 --> 01:30:27.125
Why are those people so angry?
- Because they're afraid.

632
01:30:32.500 --> 01:30:34.500
First. they betrayed us...

633
01:30:35.792 --> 01:30:39.167
to the English and now to the French.

634
01:30:39.625 --> 01:30:41.917
And De Ruyter is part of it. too.

635
01:30:42.042 --> 01:30:45.417
If he wanted.
he could have chased them off.

636
01:30:47.500 --> 01:30:50.709
I've heard that he's keeping our ships
in the harbour.

637
01:30:50.834 --> 01:30:56.709
And that Louis wil make the admiral
the Duke of Brabant.

638
01:30:56.834 --> 01:31:00.000
The prime minister
has weakened the army...

639
01:31:00.125 --> 01:31:02.834
so De Ruyter has all the power.

640
01:31:03.834 --> 01:31:06.125
Downstairs. now.

641
01:31:08.875 --> 01:31:10.542
Hide.

642
01:31:22.209 --> 01:31:27.250
Mummy. hurry up. Come on.

643
01:31:27.292 --> 01:31:28.959
Stay there.

644
01:31:37.125 --> 01:31:38.917
Let's burn his house down.

645
01:31:45.792 --> 01:31:48.542
Fire.

646
01:31:48.709 --> 01:31:52.917
Go back. Go on. Just sit there.

647
01:31:59.167 --> 01:32:01.709
Here's a blanket. madam.

648
01:32:03.959 --> 01:32:07.250
Be careful.

649
01:32:24.250 --> 01:32:27.334
Don't you have anything better to do?

650
01:32:27.500 --> 01:32:32.084
Go back to your families.
- Your husband betrayed us.

651
01:32:32.209 --> 01:32:35.375
Betrayed you? Really?

652
01:32:36.875 --> 01:32:41.167
So what did my husband do when
the English attacked us at Plymouth?

653
01:32:42.209 --> 01:32:47.459
And Ter Heijde. and Bergen
and Chatham?

654
01:32:49.459 --> 01:32:52.084
Did he betray you then?

655
01:32:52.167 --> 01:32:56.042
Or did my husband save you
and your families?

656
01:32:57.709 --> 01:33:01.959
I understand that you're afraid.
I'm afraid. too.

657
01:33:04.250 --> 01:33:09.834
So go home and let Michiel do
what he always does.

658
01:33:09.959 --> 01:33:16.000
Risking his life so that all of you
can sleep safely.

659
01:33:18.209 --> 01:33:21.917
He tried to murder the Prince.
together with De Witt.

660
01:33:47.292 --> 01:33:48.292
Don't leave. mommy.

661
01:33:48.417 --> 01:33:50.750
It'll be all right.
- I'm afraid.

662
01:34:10.459 --> 01:34:12.584
Long live France.

663
01:34:25.542 --> 01:34:30.042
You don't have a plan. admit it.
- Mr De Waerd.

664
01:34:30.167 --> 01:34:35.334
Cut it out. Stop delaying things.

665
01:34:35.459 --> 01:34:39.875
There is no time for political games.
- It isn't a political game.

666
01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:42.500
If the Prince gets in charge...

667
01:35:21.292 --> 01:35:24.667
Representative De Waerd has the floor.

668
01:35:27.792 --> 01:35:30.792
The situation is untenable.

669
01:35:30.875 --> 01:35:35.375
The only person who can save us.
is the Prince.

670
01:35:35.542 --> 01:35:41.667
The prime minister should
hand in his resignation. Immediately.

671
01:36:15.959 --> 01:36:19.125
They're waiting. Your Highness.

672
01:36:19.209 --> 01:36:22.917
It took them such a long time.
Let them wait.

673
01:36:24.750 --> 01:36:30.042
I say we appoint Tromp as the new admiral.
- Someone we can trust.

674
01:36:30.167 --> 01:36:33.709
Since when can't I trust De Ruyter?

675
01:36:33.875 --> 01:36:36.625
But. Your Highness.
he's friends with De Witt.

676
01:36:36.750 --> 01:36:41.375
Please try to understand. Kievit.
we have to work together.

677
01:36:41.500 --> 01:36:43.959
I want to be the leader
for all Dutchmen.

678
01:36:58.625 --> 01:37:02.459
Your Highness. it's an honour
and pleasure to ask you...

679
01:37:02.542 --> 01:37:07.917
on behalf of the Dutch Republic
to accept the title of king...

680
01:37:08.042 --> 01:37:11.459
like your ancestor.
William of Orange. once was.

681
01:37:12.500 --> 01:37:18.417
There is one thing
I'm really concerned about.

682
01:37:19.167 --> 01:37:24.292
Yes. we have received
some very worrying news.

683
01:37:25.417 --> 01:37:29.417
Concerning a secret plot
to assassinate the Prince.

684
01:37:29.542 --> 01:37:31.375
We also know who's behind it.

685
01:37:51.709 --> 01:37:55.209
Come on.

686
01:37:55.292 --> 01:37:57.417
Go on.

687
01:37:58.375 --> 01:38:03.417
I can make this a lot easier for you.
All you have to do. is tell the truth.

688
01:38:03.584 --> 01:38:08.959
You were part of a conspiracy
to assassinate the Prince of Orange.

689
01:38:09.084 --> 01:38:10.750
There are witnesses.

690
01:38:15.250 --> 01:38:21.167
I don't see how you want to deny...
- Yes. that's highly unfortunate.

691
01:38:43.792 --> 01:38:47.167
I can't turn this into more
than an exile.

692
01:38:47.292 --> 01:38:50.292
I assume you don't want
to end up here yourself.

693
01:39:20.417 --> 01:39:22.375
I think you should read this.

694
01:39:25.459 --> 01:39:29.792
Cornelis is accused of high treason
for plotting to kill the Prince.

695
01:39:29.917 --> 01:39:32.917
Johan asks me to testify.
- Don't be stupid.

696
01:39:33.042 --> 01:39:36.167
You heard me.
- The brothers De Witt are lost.

697
01:39:36.334 --> 01:39:39.125
Stay out of it.
- What kind of country would that be?

698
01:39:39.250 --> 01:39:42.209
I say whatever I want.
as long as I live.

699
01:39:42.292 --> 01:39:45.834
Back to shore. straight away.
Hoist the sails.

700
01:40:01.709 --> 01:40:04.292
We have to get his brother
here as well.

701
01:40:06.292 --> 01:40:10.292
Say that this comes from Cornelis.
- I don't know if I...

702
01:40:12.542 --> 01:40:15.584
We're going to be in power soon.

703
01:40:15.792 --> 01:40:19.209
We need to know who is with us
and who is not.

704
01:40:31.834 --> 01:40:35.750
There must be some kind of procedure.
- That depends on...

705
01:40:35.917 --> 01:40:37.292
A message for you.

706
01:40:44.667 --> 01:40:48.500
Excuse me.
- Something must be done.

707
01:40:48.625 --> 01:40:49.917
Come on.

708
01:41:14.584 --> 01:41:18.917
Stand aside. Move. Open up.

709
01:41:33.167 --> 01:41:35.375
It's okay. It's me.

710
01:41:35.500 --> 01:41:41.167
You shouldn't have come. It's a trap.

711
01:41:42.625 --> 01:41:45.542
Admit it. You can't do without me.

712
01:41:55.917 --> 01:41:59.917
We have to get out of here.
Can you walk? I've got you.

713
01:42:22.084 --> 01:42:26.625
And you don't know where he went?
- No. sir. I don't. Good evening.

714
01:43:52.459 --> 01:43:53.459
Traitor.

715
01:44:30.209 --> 01:44:31.709
I want to have his dick.

716
01:45:26.834 --> 01:45:27.959
Do it.

717
01:45:46.792 --> 01:45:51.375
There is De Ruyter. He's friends
with the De Witts. Get him.

718
01:45:52.292 --> 01:45:54.042
Get him.

719
01:46:20.000 --> 01:46:23.209
The heart of the prime minister.

720
01:47:01.167 --> 01:47:03.500
I thought you were at sea.
- Daddy.

721
01:47:05.250 --> 01:47:08.459
Where have you been?
- The Hague.

722
01:47:11.042 --> 01:47:14.042
Bring the children to bed.
- Come. children.

723
01:47:14.167 --> 01:47:15.792
Daddy's tired. Go on.

724
01:47:18.000 --> 01:47:19.500
Bye. daddy.

725
01:47:24.459 --> 01:47:28.417
What happened?
- I was too late. I...

726
01:47:30.917 --> 01:47:32.667
Johan...

727
01:47:50.584 --> 01:47:54.084
Gentlemen. look.
Cornelis De Witt's penis. Five cents.

728
01:47:54.209 --> 01:47:56.167
Piss off. man.

729
01:47:57.250 --> 01:47:59.000
Barbaric.

730
01:48:00.542 --> 01:48:03.042
It had to be done.

731
01:48:03.125 --> 01:48:06.417
They would've tried
to seize power again.

732
01:48:06.542 --> 01:48:09.000
We have to know who we can trust.

733
01:48:09.125 --> 01:48:14.292
We can't allow for Tromp
to serve under De Ruyter.

734
01:48:14.417 --> 01:48:17.084
I want to serve.
but not under De Ruyter.

735
01:48:17.250 --> 01:48:19.750
De Ruyter stays.

736
01:48:19.917 --> 01:48:24.000
I've appointed him for life.
and I'm a man of my word.

737
01:48:24.125 --> 01:48:25.834
Make it up with him.

738
01:48:30.459 --> 01:48:34.084
Old Tromp whispered something
to me before he died.

739
01:48:36.334 --> 01:48:41.417
About the way the wind blows. and that
an admiral has to keep his course.

740
01:48:43.334 --> 01:48:47.125
I thought he was talking nonsense.
but now I understand.

741
01:48:50.000 --> 01:48:51.209
Politics.

742
01:48:53.542 --> 01:48:56.417
Only one thing counts for an admiral.

743
01:48:58.417 --> 01:49:03.542
I've heard enough. You're going
to do what they ask of you.

744
01:49:04.959 --> 01:49:06.417
Go.

745
01:49:08.125 --> 01:49:11.459
Try to understand.
- They almost killed us too.

746
01:49:12.459 --> 01:49:13.834
I know.

747
01:49:18.792 --> 01:49:24.584
Promise me one thing. When all of this
is over. we go back to Vlissingen.

748
01:49:24.709 --> 01:49:26.459
You. me. the children.

749
01:49:30.459 --> 01:49:33.750
The army needs reinforcements here.

750
01:49:33.917 --> 01:49:38.625
The cities along the IJssel have
surrendered to the French.

751
01:49:38.750 --> 01:49:41.792
Let's turn the navy into land forces.

752
01:49:41.959 --> 01:49:44.042
Where can we cut the dikes?

753
01:49:49.459 --> 01:49:54.084
Your Highness. do you realize
what the consequences will be?

754
01:49:54.209 --> 01:49:57.709
Are you sure?
Thousands of people live there.

755
01:49:57.834 --> 01:50:01.709
All civilians. Your Highness.
- I want the exact locations.

756
01:50:03.209 --> 01:50:04.834
Leave us.

757
01:50:08.500 --> 01:50:10.000
You stay here.

758
01:50:13.125 --> 01:50:14.417
Admiral.

759
01:50:17.209 --> 01:50:19.084
Your Highness.

760
01:50:20.459 --> 01:50:23.292
I congratulate you
on your appointment.

761
01:50:26.000 --> 01:50:30.792
I know how you feel. De Ruyter.
- Do you?

762
01:50:32.334 --> 01:50:34.875
The French are nearing Amsterdam.

763
01:50:35.042 --> 01:50:39.042
The English will attack.
with the help of the French fleet.

764
01:50:43.542 --> 01:50:49.459
You have to make up with Tromp.
The country needs you. Both of you.

765
01:50:58.959 --> 01:51:00.792
I will follow your orders.

766
01:51:07.917 --> 01:51:09.584
I'm sure you will.

767
01:51:10.959 --> 01:51:12.459
You have my word.

768
01:51:12.584 --> 01:51:17.834
Well done. Gentlemen. excuse me.
we're going to flood the country.

769
01:51:48.250 --> 01:51:50.667
Huzzah for De Ruyter and Tromp.

770
01:51:57.792 --> 01:51:59.500
Let's not overdo it.

771
01:52:13.709 --> 01:52:15.834
Let's get to work.

772
01:52:31.917 --> 01:52:35.792
Welcome. admiral.

773
01:52:46.750 --> 01:52:50.125
The English receive help
from the French fleet.

774
01:52:53.000 --> 01:52:55.625
You've already started.

775
01:52:55.750 --> 01:52:59.375
According to the latest updates
they're here and here.

776
01:52:59.500 --> 01:53:03.709
Not only do they want to destroy
our ships. but go ashore as well.

777
01:53:16.209 --> 01:53:20.167
The English want an invasion.
That's to our advantage.

778
01:53:20.334 --> 01:53:25.417
They want to reach the coast. so
they'll try to go ashore here or here.

779
01:53:35.959 --> 01:53:41.334
The wind comes from the south. and
so we'll do what they expect us to do.

780
01:53:41.459 --> 01:53:44.042
We're going to sail in line here...

781
01:53:44.167 --> 01:53:49.542
and then Tromp is going to leave
a hole here. He's good at that.

782
01:53:53.125 --> 01:53:59.167
You want them to sail through.
- The tide could be in our advantage.

783
01:53:59.292 --> 01:54:00.709
It's our only chance.

784
01:54:02.584 --> 01:54:04.625
Brilliant.

785
01:54:04.750 --> 01:54:09.792
My head is like an old piss bucket.
Can someone tell me what the plan is?

786
01:54:34.459 --> 01:54:36.875
Girls. you're going with Klaartje.

787
01:54:37.000 --> 01:54:40.334
You can't go to the coast by yourself.
- Go on.

788
01:54:42.334 --> 01:54:46.625
Not through the front door.
Through the back.

789
01:55:09.417 --> 01:55:12.209
Hoist the sails. Pull the ropes.

790
01:55:55.709 --> 01:55:57.959
Keep going.

791
01:55:58.250 --> 01:56:00.084
They're taking the bait.

792
01:56:22.667 --> 01:56:24.875
Come on.

793
01:56:35.417 --> 01:56:37.417
Everyone. get off the ship.

794
01:57:02.959 --> 01:57:05.667
We're going through that hole there.

795
01:57:07.625 --> 01:57:10.000
It's our chance to reach the coast.

796
01:57:12.959 --> 01:57:15.334
Man the guns.

797
01:57:17.334 --> 01:57:20.500
Hurry up. prepare the cannons.

798
01:57:31.667 --> 01:57:35.750
For once I do what you say...
- Admiral. The French fleet arrived.

799
01:57:35.959 --> 01:57:38.250
Take the Vooruitgang.
You know the plan.

800
01:57:38.375 --> 01:57:40.417
Aye aye. admiral.

801
01:57:40.500 --> 01:57:43.584
Boatswains in front of the mast.

802
01:58:34.084 --> 01:58:36.459
Prepare to come about.

803
01:58:43.167 --> 01:58:45.042
Get ready.

804
01:58:45.167 --> 01:58:48.542
De Ruyter is trying to defend
the coast. Let's go.

805
01:59:20.125 --> 01:59:23.125
Damn it.

806
01:59:23.250 --> 01:59:25.334
Abandon ship.

807
01:59:37.125 --> 01:59:40.084
Let us come about then.

808
01:59:40.209 --> 01:59:44.000
Load starboard.

809
01:59:44.125 --> 01:59:46.209
Prepare to come about.

810
01:59:49.292 --> 01:59:50.584
Come about.

811
01:59:50.709 --> 01:59:53.917
Prepare to come about.

812
02:00:11.625 --> 02:00:13.584
Every ship should pull back.

813
02:00:13.875 --> 02:00:17.459
Lift those cannons. Up.

814
02:00:17.542 --> 02:00:19.625
Carpenters. to the front.

815
02:00:27.959 --> 02:00:30.250
Fire.

816
02:00:48.417 --> 02:00:50.625
Pull back.

817
02:00:52.000 --> 02:00:55.709
Pull back.

818
02:01:23.292 --> 02:01:25.500
To victory.

819
02:01:27.417 --> 02:01:30.459
Huzzah for De Ruyter.

820
02:01:34.584 --> 02:01:37.667
Bestevaer.

821
02:01:42.792 --> 02:01:47.125
Bestevaer.

822
02:02:07.459 --> 02:02:12.000
You know what you promised.
- Just one more talk and it's over.

823
02:02:12.084 --> 02:02:14.167
People are being arrested everywhere.

824
02:02:14.292 --> 02:02:17.875
Don't say anything foolish
to the Prince.

825
02:02:18.042 --> 02:02:22.000
There are some people here
I want to introduce you to.

826
02:02:22.125 --> 02:02:26.542
These gentleman represent
about a quarter of our army.

827
02:02:26.667 --> 02:02:28.750
You want me to join a rebellion?

828
02:02:28.834 --> 02:02:34.250
You can be the symbol of our
resistance. The people look up to you.

829
02:02:34.375 --> 02:02:38.209
And I have the fleet behind me.
You're crazy. man.

830
02:02:38.334 --> 02:02:40.834
Plunge the country into a civil war?

831
02:02:41.625 --> 02:02:45.959
Anything is better
than a dictatorship.

832
02:02:49.250 --> 02:02:52.417
A disgrace.
This is a total disgrace.

833
02:02:52.875 --> 02:02:56.000
Be careful. Michiel.
Trust no one.

834
02:03:12.500 --> 02:03:13.917
Look around you.

835
02:03:14.042 --> 02:03:17.917
That just gives
them a reason to arrest you.

836
02:03:18.042 --> 02:03:21.750
We have to show
that we can work together.

837
02:03:22.792 --> 02:03:25.500
We must rebuild this country together.

838
02:03:43.709 --> 02:03:48.584
The republicans are reorganizing.
- They want De Ruyter as their leader.

839
02:03:48.709 --> 02:03:53.750
The people love him.
- That's the problem. Your Highness.

840
02:03:53.875 --> 02:03:56.250
We have a plan to solve that problem.

841
02:04:05.125 --> 02:04:07.334
The Prince of Orange.

842
02:04:25.584 --> 02:04:27.000
Thank you.

843
02:04:31.125 --> 02:04:33.875
I would like to thank one man...

844
02:04:33.959 --> 02:04:39.417
without whom this glorious victory
would never have occurred.

845
02:04:39.584 --> 02:04:43.042
The great hero
from the Battle of Texel:

846
02:04:43.167 --> 02:04:44.667
Cornelis Tromp.

847
02:04:49.084 --> 02:04:51.542
They don't know what they're doing.

848
02:05:08.917 --> 02:05:10.334
Bravo.

849
02:05:12.459 --> 02:05:13.792
Bravo.

850
02:05:40.042 --> 02:05:43.209
Do you have a moment?
I'll be right with you.

851
02:05:56.084 --> 02:05:59.667
Retirement? Back to Zeeland?

852
02:05:59.792 --> 02:06:02.667
What will the Netherlands do
without you?

853
02:06:02.792 --> 02:06:05.834
This country has a great leader.

854
02:06:05.959 --> 02:06:08.250
The country has a great leader.

855
02:06:08.375 --> 02:06:11.459
How can I be a great leader
for all the Dutch...

856
02:06:11.584 --> 02:06:15.584
if they don't all love me?
I'm not like him.

857
02:06:16.584 --> 02:06:19.792
Your Highness
is underestimating himself.

858
02:06:21.042 --> 02:06:22.042
Are you serious?

859
02:06:22.167 --> 02:06:27.500
The king can unite the country.
Rise above the parties.

860
02:06:27.667 --> 02:06:31.209
You want me to release the rebels.
- A nice gesture.

861
02:06:31.292 --> 02:06:33.917
Have you heard
what they say about me?

862
02:06:34.000 --> 02:06:38.667
That's how they thank me.
after everything I did for my people.

863
02:06:38.792 --> 02:06:41.042
Surely you can admit that.

864
02:06:41.792 --> 02:06:45.667
Should I just watch the republicans
ruin our country?

865
02:06:45.792 --> 02:06:47.667
I can't just stand idly by.

866
02:06:47.792 --> 02:06:50.625
Like with Johan and Cornelis de Witt?

867
02:06:50.792 --> 02:06:54.334
Was that massacre also
for the good of the country?

868
02:06:54.500 --> 02:06:58.042
I had nothing...
- Nothing to do with that?

869
02:07:00.625 --> 02:07:04.042
We couldn't control the mob.
No one had any idea.

870
02:07:04.167 --> 02:07:07.500
Your people incited the nation
against the De Witts for months.

871
02:07:08.500 --> 02:07:12.834
Pamphlets. agitators.
filthy back room politics.

872
02:07:12.917 --> 02:07:14.834
How dare you?

873
02:07:14.959 --> 02:07:18.375
You'll have to live
with your conscience.

874
02:07:18.542 --> 02:07:21.334
How dare you?

875
02:07:22.167 --> 02:07:24.584
Still De Witt's friend. eh?

876
02:07:24.709 --> 02:07:28.125
I'm starting to doubt
if you'll obey me when it's needed.

877
02:07:28.250 --> 02:07:30.792
I have always served my country.

878
02:07:30.917 --> 02:07:33.917
If only the country
was as stable as you.

879
02:07:34.917 --> 02:07:38.209
Your Highness can be assured
of my dedication.

880
02:07:43.750 --> 02:07:45.167
But am I?

881
02:08:07.042 --> 02:08:08.292
Admiral.

882
02:08:14.334 --> 02:08:18.417
I hoped this wouldn't be necessary.
but my advisers were right.

883
02:08:19.709 --> 02:08:22.792
I'll accept your retirement
on one condition.

884
02:08:23.834 --> 02:08:28.792
Your Highness?
- You carry out one last mission.

885
02:08:28.917 --> 02:08:34.292
You're going to the Mediterranean Sea.
- A secret mission against the French.

886
02:08:34.459 --> 02:08:36.125
Why should I?

887
02:08:36.209 --> 02:08:39.917
It's not wise to refuse a direct order
from your Prince.

888
02:08:41.667 --> 02:08:44.875
It's hard to protect
a traitor's family.

889
02:08:51.084 --> 02:08:52.375
De Ruyter.

890
02:09:14.959 --> 02:09:20.584
I might as well have condemned him to
death. That would've been more honest.

891
02:09:20.709 --> 02:09:23.459
Think of it as an act
of a true statesman.

892
02:09:33.959 --> 02:09:37.584
I've decided to form an alliance
with the English throne.

893
02:09:39.000 --> 02:09:42.542
I have to seize this opportunity.

894
02:09:45.709 --> 02:09:48.250
A marriage with Mary Stuart.

895
02:09:53.209 --> 02:09:56.125
Think of it as an act
of a true statesman.

896
02:10:13.334 --> 02:10:15.084
I couldn't sleep either.

897
02:10:22.542 --> 02:10:24.334
Why. Michiel?

898
02:10:27.959 --> 02:10:30.375
Why did you accept that mission?

899
02:10:31.750 --> 02:10:34.125
You have nothing to prove.
They can't force us.

900
02:10:34.250 --> 02:10:36.125
That's not it.

901
02:10:36.375 --> 02:10:40.625
So you want a state funeral?
- I don't want to cause a civil war.

902
02:10:40.792 --> 02:10:45.042
And you won't. It's not your fault
those men are in prison.

903
02:10:45.167 --> 02:10:47.667
Someone has to obey the Prince.

904
02:10:47.792 --> 02:10:49.750
The Prince?

905
02:10:49.875 --> 02:10:54.292
He only wants to get rid of you.
They all want to get rid of you.

906
02:10:54.417 --> 02:10:58.584
Your success is too great.
Don't you see what they're doing?

907
02:10:58.709 --> 02:11:01.792
They want you dead.
just like with Johan.

908
02:11:01.917 --> 02:11:07.042
Someone needs to lead by example.
- A good example.

909
02:11:07.167 --> 02:11:10.709
Let someone else do it.
They always reconcile.

910
02:11:10.834 --> 02:11:14.500
Too much blood has been spilled.
The country is torn.

911
02:11:14.584 --> 02:11:17.625
I don't care if the country is torn.

912
02:11:17.709 --> 02:11:20.917
I just want us to enjoy
our retirement in peace.

913
02:11:22.875 --> 02:11:24.750
What do you mean?

914
02:11:33.750 --> 02:11:35.709
What did the Prince say?

915
02:11:36.750 --> 02:11:38.292
Did he threaten us?

916
02:11:40.584 --> 02:11:43.959
So he did.
- He wasn't even subtle about it.

917
02:11:44.042 --> 02:11:47.667
And you want to risk your life again
for a man like that?

918
02:11:48.709 --> 02:11:52.042
A man who has never cared
about other people...

919
02:11:52.125 --> 02:11:54.875
or what it's like for us
and the children.

920
02:11:55.000 --> 02:11:58.167
I do this for you and the children.

921
02:12:00.000 --> 02:12:03.334
He guarantees your safety
while I'm gone.

922
02:12:06.750 --> 02:12:09.334
And if you survive and come back?

923
02:12:11.334 --> 02:12:12.875
Will it be over then?

924
02:12:13.750 --> 02:12:15.709
Will they leave us alone?

925
02:12:21.000 --> 02:12:23.000
You're not coming back.

926
02:12:25.834 --> 02:12:29.209
You're not leaving me alone.
do you hear me?

927
02:12:30.584 --> 02:12:32.959
You're not leaving me by myself.

928
02:12:33.917 --> 02:12:38.625
Of course. darling.
Of course I'm coming back.

929
02:12:45.459 --> 02:12:46.875
No. no. no. no.

930
02:12:57.334 --> 02:12:59.000
Be a good boy.

931
02:12:59.959 --> 02:13:07.042
Raise up. Smooth.

932
02:13:14.667 --> 02:13:16.792
Daddy loves you very much.

933
02:13:22.584 --> 02:13:24.125
Forgive me. my love.

934
02:14:02.334 --> 02:14:04.250
Come on. let's go home.

935
02:14:50.334 --> 02:14:53.875
I count no more than 12 ships.
Where is the Seven Provinces?

936
02:14:58.625 --> 02:15:01.917
Is that all they have?
What's the honour in that?

937
02:15:09.625 --> 02:15:13.000
Prepare for combat. - Get ready.

938
02:15:51.250 --> 02:15:54.584
Load the cannons.

939
02:16:11.167 --> 02:16:13.334
Fire.

940
02:16:24.375 --> 02:16:26.334
Reload the cannons.

941
02:16:41.584 --> 02:16:43.542
Hurry up with those cannons.

942
02:16:53.375 --> 02:16:55.000
God damn it.

943
02:17:10.750 --> 02:17:12.959
Faster. faster.

944
02:18:33.084 --> 02:18:41.084
Fire.

945
02:19:09.792 --> 02:19:12.042
Surgeon to the top deck.

946
02:19:15.125 --> 02:19:16.959
Stay with us.

947
02:19:17.667 --> 02:19:20.584
Slightly more to port.

948
02:19:23.000 --> 02:19:24.375
Anna.

949
02:19:53.292 --> 02:19:55.625
Michiel de Ruyter is dead.

950
02:19:57.167 --> 02:20:01.917
Load the cannons with blank shells.
Let's honour our enemy.

951
02:20:02.042 --> 02:20:04.834
Get ready to pay tribute.

952
02:21:37.542 --> 02:21:40.125
Look at them.

953
02:21:40.209 --> 02:21:44.584
Orangists and republicans.
side by side for the first time.

954
02:21:49.584 --> 02:21:51.459
I never could have done that.

955
02:22:04.167 --> 02:22:05.917
I've seen enough.

956
02:22:10.667 --> 02:22:12.500
The end of an era.

957
02:22:13.834 --> 02:22:16.167
That is Anna De Ruyter.
let her through.

958
02:22:39.834 --> 02:22:44.459
Give him the most beautiful grave
possible.

959
02:22:46.667 --> 02:22:48.042
All right.
